definition.value: An ester where the ester linkage is bonded directly to an aromatic system.
An amide in which the amide linkage is bonded directly to an aromatic system.

An amino acid derivative resulting from reaction of tyrosine at the amino group or the carboxy group, any substitution of phenyl hydrogens, or from the replacement of any hydrogen of tyrosine by a heteroatom. The definition normally excludes peptides containing tyrosine residues.

A family of nitrogen molecular entities which are highly reactive and derived from nitric oxide (.NO) and superoxide (O2.(-)) produced via the enzymatic activity of inducible nitric oxide synthase 2 (NOS2) and NADPH oxidase respectively.
A dihydroxybenzoic acid that is 3,4-dihydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogen at position 5 is substituted by a nonaprenyl group.
A 3,4-dihydroxy-5-polyprenylbenzoate in which the polyprenyl chain contains 9 prenyl units; major species at pH 7.3.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid that is 4-hydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydrogens at positions 3 and 5 are substituted by a methoxy and a nonaprenyl group.
A 3-methoxy-4-hydroxy-5-all-trans-polyprenylbenzoate in which the polyprenyl chain contains 9 prenyl units; major species at pH 7.3.
A 3,4-dihydroxy-5-polyprenylbenzoate in which the polyprenyl chain contains 10 prenyl units; major species at pH 7.3.
A 3-methoxy-4-hydroxy-5-all-trans-polyprenylbenzoate in which the polyprenyl chain contains 10 prenyl units; major species at pH 7.3.
An alkane that consists of pentane bearing two methyl substituents at position 2 and a single methyl substituent at position 4.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having myristoyl (tetradecanoyl) as the 1-O-acyl group.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having linoleyl (9Z,12Z-octadecadienoyl) as the 1-O-acyl group.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having 18-mercaptooctadecanoyl as the 1-O-acyl group.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having oleoyl as the 1-O-acyl group.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 2,3-cyclic phosphate having oleoyl as the 1-O-acyl group.
A monoacylglycerol phosphate that consists of sn-glycerol 2,3-cyclic phosphate bearing an acyl group at position 1.
A 1-acyl-sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having lauroyl (dodecanoyl) as the 1-O-acyl group.
A compound of beryllium (+2 oxidation state) and chloride in the ratio 1:2.

A sulfur-containing amino acid in which the gamma-carbon atoms of two molecules of L-aminobutyric acid are joined via a thioether linkage. It is a byproduct of cystathionine-gamma-lyase and a possible human hyperhomocysteinemia marker.
An oligosaccharide comprised of xylose residues.
A carboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of a sialic acid, formed by deprotonation of the carboxy group.

An inorganic sulfate salt obtained by reaction of sulfuric acid with two equivalents of ammonia. A high-melting (decomposes above 280degreeC) white solid which is very soluble in water (70.6 g/100 g water at 0degreeC; 103.8 g/100 g water at 100degreeC), it is widely used as a fertilizer for alkaline soils.

An ammonium salt obtained by reaction of ammonia with acetic acid. A deliquescent white crystalline solid, it has a relatively low melting point (114degreeC) for a salt. Used as a food acidity regulator, although no longer approved for this purpose in the EU.
The potassium salt of aminocyclopyrachlor.
A polyprenyl glycosyl diphosphate having N-acetyl-alpha-D-glucosamine as the glycosyl fragment.
The magnesium salt of acetic acid.
An organic sodium salt which is the monosodium salt of formic acid.
A (1->4)-beta-D-glucan (cellulose) in amorphous form with a structure consisting of several hundred to over ten thousand D-glucose residues joined by beta(1->4) glycosidic linkages.
A (1->4)-beta-D-glucan (cellulose) in crystalline form with a structure consisting of several hundred to over ten thousand D-glucose residues joined by beta(1->4) glycosidic linkages.
The ammonium salt of phosphoric acid (molar ratio 1:1).
A glycol in which the two hydroxy groups are at positions 2 and 4 of 2-methylpentane (isopentane).
An inorganic sodium salt having bromide as the counterion.
The inorganic nitrate salt of sodium.
The magnesium salt of formic acid, which exists in the solid state as a dihydrate.
The organic sodium salt that is the disodium salt of L-tartaric acid.
The potassium salt of L-tartaric acid.
The organic sodium and potassium salt of L-tartaric acid (mol ratio 1:1:1).
The inorganic chloride salt of yttrium(III)
A methyl glycoside that consists of methyl alpha-D-galactoside having an alpha-D-galactosyl residue at the 4-position.
An alpha-D-mannoside having 4-aminophenyl as the anomeric substituent.
A potassium salt in which dihydrogen phosphate(1-) is the counterion.
A citrate salt in which all three carboxy groups are deprotonated and associated with ammonium ions as counter-cations.
The ammonium salt of nitric acid.
The inorganic chloride salt of caesium; each caesium ion is coordinated by eight chlorine ions.
The iodide salt of ammonia.

An inorganic chloride in which manganese(II) is coordinated to two chloride ions. In its anhydrous state manganese(II) chloride is a polymeric solid, which adopts a layered cadmium chloride-like structure.
The inorganic nitrate salt of potassium.
A hydroxypolyether in which a hydroxy-poly(ethylene oxide) chain is connected to each of the methyl groups of neopentane. It is commonly used to crystallise proteins.
The ammonium salt of formic acid.
